## 1.3 PHOSPHOROUS FIXATION - INDONESIA

*Comprehensive Technical Report for Modeling Applications*

*Management Scenario Analysis: Very Good, Normal, and Poor Agricultural
Practices*

**1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY**

This report provides peer-reviewed data on phosphorus (P) fixation in
Indonesian agricultural soils, structured for use in agronomic and
carbon credit modeling under three management scenarios. Indonesia\'s
diverse volcanic and highly weathered soils present unique P management
challenges, with fixation rates among the highest globally.

**Table 11: Key Findings - Indonesian P Fixation**

*Critical parameters for phosphorus management. These values determine
effective fertilizer requirements in tropical soils.*

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**           **Value/Range**         **Implication**
  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------
  **Base P Fixation       65-98%                  Among highest globally
  Range**                                         

  **Dominant Fixation     Al/Fe oxides and        pH-dependent, difficult
  Mechanisms**            allophanic clays        to reverse

  **Management Impact**   25-40% reduction        VGAM critical for P
                          possible                efficiency

  **P Sorption Maxima**   294-1,430 mg P/kg soil  High buffering capacity

  **First-Year P          5-25% without           75-95% unavailable to
  Recovery**              management              plants
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**2. INDONESIAN SOIL TYPES AND BASE P FIXATION**

Indonesian agricultural soils are dominated by volcanic-derived Andisols
in highland areas and highly weathered Ultisols/Oxisols in lowland
regions. P sorption characteristics vary significantly based on parent
material, weathering stage, and clay mineralogy.

**Table 12: Indonesian Soil Types - Base P Fixation Parameters**

*Soil-specific phosphorus fixation rates. Volcanic soils show extreme P
fixation requiring specialized management.*

  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Soil Type**     **pH      **P        **Primary         **Source**
                    Range**   Fixation   Mechanism**       
                              %**                          
  ----------------- --------- ---------- ----------------- ------------------------
  **Silandic        5.0-6.5   \>90%      Allophane,        Gonzalez-Rodriguez &
  Andosol**                              non-crystalline   Fernandez-Marcos
                                         Al/Fe             (2018)^14^

  **Vitric          5.5-6.8   65-96%     Crystalline Fe    Gonzalez-Rodriguez &
  Andosol**                              oxides            Fernandez-Marcos
                                                           (2018)^14^

  **Ultisols**      4.0-5.5   70-90%     Fe/Al oxides,     Mabagala et al.
                                         kaolinite         (2022)^15^

  **Oxisols**       4.0-5.2   70-90%     Gibbsite,         Mabagala et al.
                                         goethite          (2022)^15^

  **Inceptisols**   5.0-6.5   40-60%     Clay minerals,    Prasetyo & Suriadikarta
                                         limited oxides    (2006)^16^

  **Mollisols       6.0-7.5   25-45%     Ca-P              FAO Fertilizer Bulletin
  (Alluvial)**                           precipitation     18^17^
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

> ¹⁴ Journal of Soil Science and Plant Nutrition
>
> ¹⁵ Geoderma Regional
>
> ¹⁶ Indonesian Soil Research Institute
>
> ¹⁷ FAO Corporate Document Repository

