**What is Chitosan?**

Chitosan (C₆H₁₁NO₄)ₙ is a deacetylated derivative of chitin, produced by
removing acetyl groups (CH₃CO) from chitin through alkaline
hydrolysis.⁵³ When approximately 50% or more of the acetyl groups are
removed, the resulting polymer becomes soluble in dilute acidic
solutions and is classified as chitosan.⁵⁴ The degree of deacetylation
(DD) typically ranges from 60% to 100%, with agricultural-grade chitosan
commonly having 75-85% DD.⁵⁵ This deacetylation process transforms
chitin\'s rigid, insoluble structure into a more flexible, bioactive
polymer with enhanced solubility and antimicrobial properties.⁵⁶

**Main Chitosan Application Methods**

