## 2.D CHITIN DISEASE REFERENCES

**Historical Development and Current Applications**

Chitin first emerged as a crop protection input in the 1960s-70s, when
trials in Japan and Europe showed that adding shrimp/crab shell waste to
soil led to disease suppression and strengthened plant immunity. The
effect was subsequently linked to induced systemic resistance (ISR) and
an enriched, disease-suppressive soil microbiome.⁶⁵ Chitosan---a
partially deacetylated, water-soluble form of chitin---was later
commercialized for use as a direct foliar spray and seed treatment.⁶⁶

**Table 36: Summary Table: Chitin vs Chitosan Agricultural Use**

*CFI chitin provides one-time, fully organic field amendment. Chitosan
requires multiple applications with regulatory restrictions.*

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**     **Chitin        **Chitosan (Processed)**
                    (CFI/Shell)**   
  ----------------- --------------- ---------------------------------------
  **Typical         1-2 t/ha/yr     0.2-2 kg/ha/spray (foliar)
  Application       (soil)          
  Rate**                            

  **Typical         1× per year     3-7× per season
  Frequency**                       

  **Organic         Yes             OMRI allowed, but often classified as
  Compliance**                      synthetic if highly processed

  **Soil Limit**    No strict limit Usually \<20-50 kg/ha/yr (if allowed)

  **Cost per ha**   \$80-\$180      \$54-\$240 (season, foliar)
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------

> ⁶⁷ Standard use: CFI applied at 1,000-2,000 kg/ha/year supplies
> 180-700 kg chitin per hectare
>
> ⁶⁸ Environmental status: CFI chitin accepted globally as biofertilizer
> with no practical upper limit

**Critical Finding: The Chitosan Dominance**

The most significant discovery from comprehensive research is that the
agricultural community has largely shifted from pure chitin to chitosan
(its deacetylated derivative) for practical applications. From
2019-2024, the overwhelming majority of published studies focus on
chitosan rather than pure chitin due to superior solubility,
bioavailability, and direct antimicrobial properties.⁶⁹

**Recent Peer-Reviewed Studies on Chitin (2019-2024)**

***Systemic disease resistance through chitin soil amendment***

> Makechemu, M., Goto, Y., Zbinden, H., Widrig, V., Keller, B., Zipfel,
> C. (2024). Chitin Soil Amendment Triggers Systemic Plant Disease
> Resistance Through Enhanced Pattern-Triggered Immunity. Plant
> Biotechnology Journal. DOI: 10.1111/pbi.70282
>
> This groundbreaking 2024 study demonstrates that crab chitin flakes
> applied as soil amendments potentiate pattern-triggered immunity (PTI)
> across multiple plant species including lettuce, tomato, wheat, and
> Arabidopsis. Chitin perception in roots strengthens expression of key
> PTI components in distal leaves, creating systemic disease resistance
> against Pseudomonas syringae pv. tomato DC3000 and Blumeria graminis
> (powdery mildew).⁷⁰

***Rice disease resistance mediated by chitin***

> Takagi, M., Hotamori, K., Naito, K., et al. (2022). Chitin-induced
> systemic disease resistance in rice requires both OsCERK1 and OsCEBiP
> and is mediated via perturbation of cell-wall biogenesis in leaves.
> Frontiers in Plant Science. DOI: 10.3389/fpls.2022.1064628
>
> Testing both chitin oligomers (COs) and chitin nanofiber (CNF) at 0.1%
> and 0.01% concentrations in rice against Bipolaris oryzae (rice brown
> spot), this study found statistically significant reduction in lesion
> diameter (p \< 0.05) with soil supplementation.⁷¹

## 2.E CHITIN SOURCES INDONESIA

Indonesian crustacean processing generates 376,650-544,050 metric tons
of shell waste annually, representing a largely untapped source of
chitin---a biopolymer with profound agricultural value.⁷² This waste
contains 18-35% chitin by dry weight, offering both nutritional value
and potent bioactive properties for crop protection.⁷³

**1.1 Indonesian Shrimp Processing Industry Overview**

Indonesia\'s shrimp processing sector produces 925,700 MT of whole
crustaceans annually, with Pacific white shrimp (Litopenaeus vannamei)
comprising 63.3% (585,900 MT) and black tiger prawn (Penaeus monodon)
comprising 22.6% (209,100 MT) of total production.⁷⁴

Processing Workflow: At facilities such as PT Bahari Makmur Sejati
(Balikpapan), whole shrimp enter processing lines where heads are
removed via guillotine cut at Station 1, representing 33-40% of body
weight. Station 2 employs calibrated roller pressure to peel shell
segments (12-15% of body weight), with tail fans and processing losses
accounting for an additional 8-13%.⁷⁵ The export product---pristine
frozen meat representing only 35-45% of input biomass---leaves 55-60% as
waste requiring disposal.

East Kalimantan\'s processing infrastructure includes 12 major
facilities with combined annual capacity of 12,675 MT whole shrimp,
generating 6,973-8,240 MT wet waste or 1,743-2,060 MT dry matter
equivalent at 25% dry matter content.⁷⁶

