**3.1 Iron (Fe) - 0.2-0.4 kg Fe - Replacement Value: \$8-\$11**

**3.1.1 What is in CFI?**

One tonne of CFI contains approximately 0.2-0.4 kg iron, primarily from
BSF larvae biomass, manure and plant residues. In CFI, iron is naturally
chelated by organic acids and humic substances, which helps maintain Fe
solubility and plant availability across variable soil pH conditions.⁸¹

**3.1.2 Synthetic Replacement Cost - EDTA-Fe Benchmark**

The standard synthetic comparator is EDTA-Fe chelate, widely used in
fertigation and foliar mixes:⁸²

> • Bulk EDTA-Fe products are typically \$2-\$3/kg product
>
> • With \~13% Fe content, this equates to \~\$15-\$25/kg Fe in chelated
> form⁸³

**Valuation logic for CFI Fe:**

> • 0.2-0.4 kg Fe in CFI
>
> • At \$20-\$55/kg Fe (farm-gate pricing for chelated Fe)
>
> • Equivalent to \$8-\$11 per tonne of CFI⁷⁹

**3.1.3 CFI vs Synthetic Iron - The Critical Difference**

***CFI Benefits:***

> • Iron is naturally chelated by organic compounds in CFI, keeping it
> plant-available without expensive synthetic chelates⁸⁴
>
> • Slow release from decomposing organic matter matches crop demand
> over the season
>
> • Organic chelation protects Fe from oxidation and precipitation into
> unavailable forms (ferric oxides/hydroxides)⁸⁵
>
> • This reduces or eliminates the need for repeated, high-cost foliar
> Fe chelate sprays⁸⁶

***Synthetic Problems:***

> • In alkaline/calcareous soils, Fe sulfate oxidizes quickly and
> precipitates as rust within days⁸⁷
>
> • Farmers must resort to EDTA/EDDHA chelates at \$12-\$25/kg Fe
> wholesale and \$20-\$60/kg Fe retail⁸⁸

# 3.2. SECONDARY MACRONUTRIENTS

**Replacement Value \$10-\$23 per tonne CFI⁸⁹**

CFI supplies three key secondary macronutrients \-- magnesium (Mg),
sulfur (S) and calcium (Ca) \-- in organically bound forms from BSF
larvae, frass, manure and shell-based inputs. These nutrients are
essential for chlorophyll formation, protein synthesis, oil content,
cell walls, enzyme activation and overall crop health.⁸⁹

