**CALCULATION METHODOLOGY**

Formula:

-   Protein Price (\$/kg) = Market Price (\$/t) ÷ CP (kg/t)

-   CFI Equivalent Value = CFI Protein Content (271.2 kg) × Protein
    Price (\$/kg)

**3.3.2 Soybean Meal Equivalent by Region**

**Global Benchmark: \$174-\$217 per tonne CFI**

The December 2025 USDA Economic Research Service forecast lists soybean
meal at \$308/t (\$280/short ton), while World Bank/IndexMundi reports
\$353-358/t CIF Rotterdam for Argentine 45/46% extraction meal.
High-protein soybean meal (45-48% CP) is the baseline protein source in
poultry, swine, cattle, and aquaculture diets because of:⁹⁶

-   Good amino acid profile (especially lysine)

-   High digestibility when properly heat-treated

-   Global availability and liquid markets

Calculation:

-   At 45-48% CP (450-480 kg protein/t), protein costs \$0.64-\$0.80 per
    kg

    -   Low: \$308 ÷ 480 kg = \$0.64/kg

    -   High: \$358 ÷ 450 kg = \$0.80/kg

-   CFI Value: 271.2 kg × \$0.64-\$0.80 = \$174-\$217 per tonne CFI

**Europe CIF Rotterdam: \$190-\$201 per tonne CFI**

European soybean meal prices (€307-318/t CIF Rotterdam, June 2025 =
\$322-334/t) reflect the benchmark for EU feed manufacturers.

Calculation:

-   At 45-46% CP (450-460 kg protein/t), protein costs \$0.70-\$0.74 per
    kg

    -   Low: \$322 ÷ 460 kg = \$0.70/kg

    -   High: \$334 ÷ 450 kg = \$0.74/kg

-   CFI Value: 271.2 kg × \$0.70-\$0.74 = \$190-\$201 per tonne CFI

**Indonesia CIF: \$260-\$309 per tonne CFI**

Indonesia imports 5.5 million tonnes of soybean meal annually, primarily
for its 94 poultry feed mills.⁹⁸ CIF prices at Surabaya/Jakarta
(\$470-535/t) are significantly higher than global benchmarks due to
freight, import duties, and distribution costs.

Calculation:

-   At 47-49% CP (470-490 kg protein/t), protein costs \$0.96-\$1.14 per
    kg

    -   Low: \$470 ÷ 490 kg = \$0.96/kg

    -   High: \$535 ÷ 470 kg = \$1.14/kg

-   CFI Value: 271.2 kg × \$0.96-\$1.14 = \$260-\$309 per tonne CFI

This \$260-\$309 per tonne represents the most relevant protein
replacement value for CFI\'s target Indonesian market, recognising that
in soil, CFI\'s protein is converted slowly to plant-available nitrogen
and carbon rather than being fed directly to animals.⁹⁷

**SOURCES**

⁹⁶ Feedstuffs Ingredient Analysis; NRC Nutrient Requirements of Swine
(2012)

⁹⁷ Soil protein mineralization follows first-order kinetics with typical
half-lives of 30-90 days

⁹⁸ USDA FAS Indonesia Oilseeds Report (July 2025): Indonesia soybean
meal consumption forecast 5.5 MMT for 2025/26

Price Sources:

-   USDA ERS Soybeans & Oil Crops Market Outlook (Sept 2025):
    \$280/short ton = \$308/MT

-   World Bank/IndexMundi (May-June 2025): \$353-358/MT CIF Rotterdam

-   USDA AMS Monthly Animal By-Product Report (Dec 5, 2025): Blood meal
    \$876-\$1,160/t FOB US

-   TradeWheel Indonesia: Soybean meal \$470-535/t CIF Surabaya

-   Fastmarkets (Nov 2025): EU Category 3 blood meal €525/t EXW Eastern
    Europe

# 4. ORGANIC MATTER AND SOIL VALUE

**Replacement Value: \$160-\$270 per tonne CFI⁹⁸**

CFI improves soil quality through multiple interconnected mechanisms:
building soil organic matter (SOM) and stable humus, enhancing soil
structure and aggregation, increasing cation exchange capacity (CEC),
improving water retention and infiltration, and stimulating microbial
and biological activity. Together, these functions deliver an estimated
soil value of \$160-\$270 per tonne of CFI.⁹⁸

**Table 42: Soil Function Value per 1 tonne CFI**

*Multiple soil improvement mechanisms provide long-term productivity
gains. Value exceeds simple nutrient replacement.*

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Soil Function**                                **Value per t CFI
                                                   (USD)**
  ------------------------------------------------ ----------------------
  **Soil Organic Matter & Humus (586.7 kg/t OM)**  \$80-\$120

  **Soil Structure & Aggregation (15-30% gain)**   \$30-\$50

  **Water-Holding Capacity (15-30% increase)**     \$40-\$80

  **Cation Exchange Capacity Enhancement (CEC)**   \$10-\$20

  **Microbial & Biological Activity (50-200% ↑)**  \$15-\$25

  **Total Soil Value**                             **\$160-\$270**
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

> ⁹⁸ Soil value calculations based on replacement cost method and
> productivity gains
>
> ⁹⁹ Long-term benefits compound over multiple seasons

**3.4.1 Soil Organic Matter (SOM) and Humus**

***Replacement Value: \$80-\$120 per tonne CFI⁹⁸***

**3.4.1.1 What Is in CFI?**

Each tonne of CFI contains about 586.7 kg of organic matter, including
approximately 271 kg of protein, 54-57 kg of chitin, and \~258 kg of
additional organic carbon.⁹⁸ This mixture spans:

> • Active fractions (weeks-months) - quickly decomposed compounds
> feeding microbes¹⁰⁰
>
> • Intermediate fractions (years) - partially stabilised carbon that
> underpins medium-term fertility¹⁰¹
>
> • Stable humus fractions (decades-centuries) - long-lived carbon that
> drives CEC, structure and buffering¹⁰¹

Humus is particularly important: it is highly charged, strongly
water-holding, and resistant to rapid decomposition, making it the
\"long-term bank account\" of soil fertility.¹⁰²

**3.4.1.2 Replacement Benchmark - Compost / Topsoil**

The closest functional substitute is commercial compost or organic
topsoil amendments, typically priced at \$80-\$150 per tonne depending
on region, feedstock and maturity.⁹⁸

However, CFI\'s multipool composition (protein + chitin + complex
organics) and high biological activation often make it more functionally
potent than generic compost:

> • Compost quality is highly variable (immature, low-N, low energy)¹⁰³
>
> • CFI offers consistent, high-value organic matter with known
> composition⁹⁸

**3.4.2 Soil Structure and Aggregation**

***Replacement Value: \$30-\$50 per tonne CFI⁹⁸***

**3.4.2.1 How CFI Improves Structure**

Soil structure refers to how particles are arranged into aggregates
(\"crumbs\") with pore spaces for air and water. CFI improves structure
via three mechanisms:¹⁰⁴

> • Microbial glues - Bacteria and fungi consuming CFI\'s active OM
> produce gums and polysaccharides that cement particles together
>
> • Root exudates - Enhanced root growth from CFI nutrition increases
> root-derived binding agents
>
> • Physical binding - Chitin and humic substances act as physical
> bridges between soil particles

**3.5 Soil Amendments Needed to prevent N leaching and increase organic
matter in soils.**

**Soil Amendments: Application, Mechanism, and Nutrient Retention**

**3.5.1. Executive Summary**

This report synthesizes peer-reviewed evidence on soil amendments for
tropical and intensive agricultural systems (Oil Palm, Coffee, Rice). It
clarifies that while compost is traditionally applied at high tonnages
(20--60 t/ha) to physically ameliorate soil and supply bulk carbon,
high-efficiency amendments like Black Soldier Fly (BSF) frass can
achieve similar nutrient-use efficiency at much lower rates (2--3 t/ha)
when strategically enhanced.

The primary mechanism reducing nutrient leaching is the increase in
**Cation Exchange Capacity (CEC)** and **Water Holding Capacity (WHC)**,
driven by stable organic matter (humus) and humic substances. To
replicate the \"sponge\" effect of bulk compost using low-volume
amendments (like CFI/BSF), co-composting with **biochar** is the most
effective, scientifically validated solution.

**3.5.2. Compost & Soil Amendment Baselines**

Compost-type organic amendments are typically applied at
tonne‑per‑hectare rates on an annual or multi‑year basis. Their primary
function is to add organic matter that improves structure, nutrient
retention, and water holding, thereby reducing leaching losses.

**Mechanism of Action:**

-   **Leaching Control:** The main substances that reduce leaching are
    stable organic matter and humic substances. These increase the
    soil\'s **Cation Exchange Capacity (CEC)**, which acts as a magnetic
    trap for nutrients (ammonium, potassium, calcium), preventing them
    from washing away with rain.

-   **Water Retention:** Humified organic matter and resulting
    structural improvements (aggregation) physically hold water in soil
    pores, reducing rapid drainage that carries dissolved nutrients.

-   **Organic Matter Content:** Compost typically contains **30--60%
    organic matter** (dry basis). This bulk carbon is the engine for
    long-term soil fertility
    improvements.[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih+1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6961520/)​

**3.5.3 Crop-Specific Application Rates & Trials**

**3.1 Oil Palm (Elaeis guineensis)**

-   **Standard Amendment:** Empty Fruit Bunch (EFB), either fresh
    (mulch) or composted.

-   **Application Rates:**

    -   **Standard Practice:** 40--60 t/ha of fresh EFB every 1--2 years
        (often rotational).

    -   **Compost Equivalent:** \~20--30 t/ha of EFB compost annually
        provides similar agronomic
        benefits.Section17_Compost_Requirements.docx​[sciencedirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030147972200946X)​

-   **Field Trial Evidence (Sumatra):**

    -   A 15-year long-term trial (Tao et al., 2017) compared EFB rates
        of 30, 60, and 90 t/ha against a mineral control.

    -   **Finding:** The **30 t/ha/year** rate maintained yields
        comparable to full mineral fertilizer. Higher rates (60--90
        t/ha) provided no additional yield benefit on loam/clay-loam
        soils, establishing 30 t/ha as the practical agronomic ceiling
        for nutrient
        supply.[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6961520/)​Section17_Compost_Requirements.docx​

-   **Soil Context (Clay vs. Sandy):**

    -   **Sandy Soils (Spodosols):** Higher rates (60+ t/ha) are often
        used to build a physical moisture barrier, as leaching and
        drought are the primary yield
        limiters.[academia](https://www.academia.edu/84780920/Fertilizer_management_effects_on_oil_palm_yield_and_nutrient_use_efficiency_on_sandy_soils_with_limited_water_supply_in_Central_Kalimantan)​

    -   **Clay Soils (Ultisols - e.g., East Kalimantan):** Moderate
        rates (20--30 t/ha) are sufficient to alleviate P-fixation and
        acidity. The \"heavy\" clay needs organic matter to fluff the
        soil and unlock phosphorus, not just hold
        water.[jeeng](https://www.jeeng.net/pdf-108635-40035?filename=40035.pdf)​

-   **Application Method:** Surface banding or mulching in the
    inter-rows or weeded palm circles to maximize root contact and mulch
    protection.

**3.5.4 Arabica Coffee (Coffea arabica)**

-   **Standard Amendment:** Coffee pulp compost, Farmyard Manure (FYM),
    or Vermicompost.

-   **Application Rates:**

    -   **Typical Recommendation:** **5--7.5 t/ha/year** of
        compost/manure, or approx. 6--10 kg per tree
        annually.[arcjournals+1](https://www.arcjournals.org/pdfs/ijrsas/v4-i7/3.pdf)​

    -   **Intensive Organic:** Trials in Karnataka, India, showed 5 t/ha
        of enriched compost sustained yields comparable to conventional
        management.[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10850899/)​Section17_Compost_Requirements.docx​

-   **Field Trial Evidence:**

    -   Multi-year conversion trials in India and Latin America confirm
        that 5--10 t/ha rates maintain yield while significantly
        improving soil aggregate stability and CEC compared to
        mineral-only plots.

-   **Application Method:** Applied annually in bands along the drip
    line or in shallow basins. This placement intercepts leaching water
    directly above the feeder
    roots.[article.sciencepublishinggroup+1](https://article.sciencepublishinggroup.com/pdf/plant.20210903.15)​

**3.5.5 Rice Paddy (Oryza sativa)**

-   **Standard Amendment:** Farmyard Manure (FYM), Rice Straw Compost.

-   **Application Rates:**

    -   **Range:** **5--20 t/ha/year** or per crop
        cycle.[sciencedirect+1](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2095311923000497)​

    -   **Optimization:** Long-term trials show that integrating
        **2.5--6 t/ha** of manure with mineral fertilizer is the \"sweet
        spot\" for maximizing Nitrogen Use Efficiency (NUE) and
        minimizing
        losses.[nature+1](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-025-20125-3)​

-   **Field Trial Evidence:**

    -   Long-term experiments (20+ years) in Japan and China show that
        continuous manure application (even at lower rates of 5--10
        t/ha) increases soil carbon stocks by 30--40% over decades,
        creating a buffer that reduces N runoff and ammonia
        volatilization.[sciencedirect+1](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0016706122002993)​

-   **Application Method:** Incorporated into the soil during puddling
    (land preparation) to retain ammonium on soil colloids before
    flooding.

**3.5.6 Maize/Cereals (Additional Crop)**

-   **Standard Amendment:** Cattle Manure, Vermicompost.

-   **Application Rates:**

    -   **Integrated Systems:** **2.5--15 t/ha** of
        FYM/compost.[semanticscholar+1](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/93f66af2f309d7d9ae97067a40bd7607c7a506ea)​

-   **Field Trial Evidence:**

    -   Multi-decade trials show that even low rates (2.5 t/ha) combined
        with mineral fertilizer result in higher soil microbial biomass
        and better N retention than fertilizer alone. Vermicompost is
        often effective at lower rates (1.5--3 t/ha) due to higher
        nutrient
        availability.Section17_Compost_Requirements.docx​[semanticscholar](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/93f66af2f309d7d9ae97067a40bd7607c7a506ea)​

**4. Increasing CEC & Retention in High-Efficiency Fertilizers
(CFI/BSF)**

**The Challenge:** How to make 2--3 t/ha of CFI (BSF Frass) hold
water/nutrients like 30 t/ha of compost?

**4.1 The Role of Black Soldier Fly (BSF) Frass**

-   **Natural CEC:** BSF frass naturally contains humic-like substances
    from insect digestion, which provides a higher CEC per gram than raw
    manure.

-   **Chitin Benefit:** It contains \~4--5% chitin. Chitin amendments
    increase water retention by promoting fungal mycelial networks that
    bind soil particles into water-stable
    aggregates.[frontiersin+1](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/plant-science/articles/10.3389/fpls.2025.1509643/full)​

-   **Limitation:** At 3 t/ha, the *total* volume of organic sponge
    added is small compared to 30 t/ha of EFB.

**4.1 The Solution: Biochar Co-Composting**

Peer-reviewed \"deep research\" identifies **Biochar** as the missing
link to high retention at low volumes.

-   **Why Biochar?** Biochar is a permanent, highly porous carbon
    structure. It has a massive surface area and high CEC (after
    aging/composting).

-   **The Synergy:**

    -   **Trials:** Co-composting BSF frass with 5--20% biochar
        significantly increases the final product\'s water holding
        capacity and CEC compared to frass
        alone.[core+1](https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/481484792.pdf)​

    -   **Mechanism:** The biochar acts as a rigid sponge that doesn\'t
        degrade. The BSF frass \"charges\" this sponge with nutrients
        and microbes.

    -   **Result:** A 3 t/ha application of **BSF-Biochar blend** can
        offer water retention benefits closer to bulk compost because
        the water storage sites (pores) are far more concentrated and
        stable.[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih+1](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10144396/)​

**4.2 Recommendation for Low-Rate Application**

To replace bulk compost in leaching-prone soils (sandy) or
nutrient-locking soils (clay/Ultisols) using CFI:

1.  **Modify the Product:** Blend CFI with **5--10% Biochar**.

2.  **Target the Application:** Do not broadcast. Apply in a
    concentrated ring (weeded circle) to create a zone of high retention
    around the roots.

3.  **Humic Addition:** Adding soluble **Humic Acids** (1--2 kg/ha
    equivalent) can instantly boost the CEC of the root zone, acting as
    a \"chemical sponge\" to complement the \"physical sponge\" of the
    biochar/frass.[frontiersin+1](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/agronomy/articles/10.3389/fagro.2022.848621/full)​

