# 7.0 EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

The Indonesian palm oil industry represents the world\'s largest
producer with 46.8 million tonnes of Crude Palm Oil (CPO) annually,
generating 51.5 million tonnes of Empty Fruit Bunches (EFB) waste that
creates 38.9 million tonnes CO₂e emissions - representing 15-20% of
Indonesia\'s total GHG emissions, largely unreported in corporate
disclosures.¹⁹¹

Our analysis of the 11 major Indonesian palm oil producers controlling
2.65 million hectares reveals they generate 11.36 million tonnes of EFB
waste annually with zero commercial value. These companies face a
combined \$707 million annual revenue loss from mandatory domestic
market obligations while only 27% (3 of 11) are prepared for EUDR/CSRD
compliance.¹⁹²

Despite massive government incentives including tax holidays, import
duty exemptions, and 300% R&D deductions, zero commercial EFB-to-ethanol
plants exist globally. Production costs of \$2.50-3.50/liter versus
\$0.70 gasoline make the technology economically unviable.¹⁹³

Integration with Indonesia\'s shrimp industry, producing 38,500 MT/month
processing capacity with 15,400 MT/month waste, offers enhanced chitin
content opportunities. Three key zones - Balikpapan, Berau, and
Tarakan - provide co-location advantages with specific palm oil
operations.¹⁹⁴

# 7.1 GLOBAL PALM OIL OVERVIEW

Palm oil is the world\'s most consumed vegetable oil, accounting for
approximately 35% of global vegetable oil production. Indonesia and
Malaysia dominate global CPO production, accounting for over 80% of
world supply.¹⁹⁵

## 7.1.1 Palm Oil Uses and Applications

Palm oil\'s unique properties make it indispensable across multiple
industries. Approximately 70% is used in food products, 20% in cosmetics
and personal care, and 10% in industrial applications including
biodiesel production.¹⁹⁶

## 7.1.2 Environmental and Social Challenges

The industry faces significant criticism for deforestation, biodiversity
loss, and carbon emissions. Peatland drainage alone contributes 15-20%
of Indonesia\'s total GHG emissions. However, palm oil produces 4-10
times more oil per hectare than alternative crops, making complete
replacement challenging.¹⁹⁷

