# 7.5 EXPORT VS DOMESTIC MARKET REQUIREMENTS

Indonesian producers face mandatory domestic market obligations at
government-controlled prices, creating significant revenue losses.
Indonesia currently exports approximately 42-48% of its total palm oil
production, with the remainder consumed domestically.²¹⁴

**Key Market Dynamics:**

• Export reference price (Nov 2025): \$964/tonne - used to calculate
export tax and levy

• Domestic fixed price: \$560/tonne - creating \$404/tonne differential

• Total export fees: \$220/tonne (10% of sales + additional duty)

• FOSFA CIF Rotterdam price: \~\$1,350/tonne (mid-November 2025)

• EU green premium: +\$70-120/tonne for certified, EUDR-ready CPO

Domestic Priority: Indonesia\'s domestic consumption share has grown
from 30% historically to nearly 50% today, driven by its biodiesel
program. The sales price for the domestic market is fixed at \$560
currently. Exporting means that at a minimum, companies benefit with an
additional \$184 per tonne when selling at the government referenced
price.

Current \"green premium\" in Europe for physical certified CPO
(Segregated/IP, deforestation-free, EUDR-ready) supplied to EU buyers,
receive a premium price which is +\$70 to \$120 a tonne.

# 7.6 CSRD, ESRS E1 AND SCOPE 3 GREENHOUSE GAS EMISSIONS

The **Corporate Sustainability Reporting Directive (CSRD)** introduces
mandatory and harmonised sustainability reporting requirements for
companies operating in, or materially connected to, the European Union.
Under CSRD, companies are required to disclose climate-related
information in accordance with the **European Sustainability Reporting
Standards (ESRS)**, including comprehensive reporting of greenhouse gas
(GHG) emissions across **Scopes 1, 2, and 3**.

Within this framework, **ESRS E1 (Climate Change)** defines the specific
disclosure requirements for GHG emissions. ESRS E1 requires companies to
identify, measure, and report **material Scope 3 emissions across their
value chain**, covering both upstream supplier activities and downstream
product use. Importantly, the standard goes beyond the disclosure of
aggregate emissions totals and requires transparency on methodologies,
system boundaries, assumptions, and data quality, including the
proportion of emissions calculated using primary supplier data versus
secondary or modeled estimates.

For palm oil, the majority of climate-related impacts occur **upstream
of the reporting company's own operations**, and therefore fall
predominantly within **Scope 3 Category 1 (Purchased Goods and
Services)** as defined by the GHG Protocol. In this context, CSRD and
ESRS E1 require palm oil buyers not only to report total Scope 3
emissions, but also to clearly explain which Scope 3 categories are
considered significant, which stages of the palm oil value chain are
included, and how emissions are quantified and substantiated.

In particular, **ESRS E1-6** explicitly requires disclosure of emissions
from each **significant Scope 3 category**, together with a description
of reporting boundaries and the share of emissions based on **primary
data obtained from value-chain partners**. This requirement materially
increases the level of scrutiny applied to palm oil supply chains and
makes upstream impacts **auditable and comparable** across reporting
periods.

Palm oil Scope 3 emissions comprise both **land-use change at plantation
level** and **recurring operational emissions associated with milling
and residue management**. Land-use change emissions are treated as a
distinct hotspot due to their magnitude, historical nature, and
dependence on land history and geographic context. In contrast,
emissions arising from **Palm Oil Mill Effluent (POME) methane** and the
**management or disposal of solid residues such as Empty Fruit Bunches
(EFB)** represent ongoing, facility-level emissions that occur on a
recurring basis and can be addressed through targeted operational
interventions.

**Table 83** summarises the principal palm oil--related Scope 3
emissions sources under ESRS E1, distinguishing between formal GHG
Protocol categories and the key upstream hotspots within Scope 3
Category 1 that are most relevant for risk management, emissions
reduction, and CSRD-compliant disclosure.

