# Industry Overview: Key Findings

## Common Waste Management Practices

The Indonesian palm oil industry has evolved significantly in its waste
management approaches, with the following patterns emerging across major
producers:

### EFB (Empty Fruit Bunches) Management

Mulching: The most common practice, where EFB is applied directly to
plantations. Each mill produces 23-28% of FFB weight as EFB
(approximately 200-280 kg per tonne of FFB processed).

Composting: Increasingly adopted, often combined with POME (Palm Oil
Mill Effluent) at typical ratio of 1:3 (EFB:POME) by weight. Composting
reduces volume, improves nutrient availability, and produces
SNI-compliant organic fertilizer.

Biogas Production: Advanced mills use anaerobic digestion with methane
capture facilities. This can reduce mill GHG emissions by 40-90% while
generating renewable electricity.

Mushroom Cultivation: Emerging practice where EFB serves as substrate
for straw mushroom or oyster mushroom cultivation, with yields of 47-282
kg per tonne of EFB.

Bio-oil and Bioethanol: Through pyrolysis (400-600°C) or glucose
extraction, EFB can produce liquid fuels. Government initiatives
exploring this pathway for energy transition.

Pelletization: EFB converted to fuel pellets (6-10mm diameter) for
export markets, particularly to Japan and South Korea for biomass power
plants.

### PKF/PKS (Palm Kernel Fiber/Shell) Management

Boiler Fuel: Primary use across all mills. PKS provides 2.0 MW per
60-ton/hour mill capacity; fiber provides \~1.5 MW. Palm biomass makes
mills energy self-sufficient.

Electricity Generation: Cogeneration systems produce steam and power.
Total Indonesian potential: 4,336 MW from palm mill biomass.

PKS Export Market: High-value commodity exported to Japan (1.3 million
tonnes in 2023, 75% from Indonesia), South Korea, and Europe for biomass
power plants. PKS emits 70% less CO₂ than coal per energy unit.

Activated Carbon: PKS processed into activated carbon for water
filtration and air purification systems.

### Industry Challenges and Trends

• Regulatory Pressure: Indonesian government banned open burning of EFB
due to air pollution. POME methane emissions increasingly regulated.

• Technology Adoption Gap: Most mills (70%+) still use simple mulching.
Advanced technologies require high capital investment.

• EU Deforestation Regulation (EUDR): Effective January 2025, requires
demonstration of deforestation-free and legally compliant supply chains.

• Carbon Credit Opportunities: ACM0022 methodology allows mills with
methane capture to generate carbon credits.

• Circular Economy Focus: Increasing integration of waste streams (EFB +
POME co-digestion, spent mushroom substrate for biogas).

# Detailed Company Profile 1: Golden Agri Resources (GAR) / Sinar Mas Group

## Company Overview

Golden Agri Resources (GAR), operating as PT SMART Tbk in Indonesia, is
one of the world\'s largest palm oil producers and a key subsidiary of
the Sinar Mas Group. Listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange since 1999,
GAR represents the agribusiness arm of the influential Widjaja family\'s
diversified conglomerate.

### Operational Scale

• Plantation Area: Over 450,000 hectares across Indonesia (Bangka
Belitung, Central Kalimantan, East Kalimantan, Jambi, Lampung, North
Sumatra, Papua, Riau, South Kalimantan, South Sumatra, West Kalimantan)

• Mills: Approximately 50+ palm oil mills with integrated operations

• Production Capacity: Processes millions of tonnes of Fresh Fruit
Bunches (FFB) annually

• Market Position: Singapore Stock Exchange listed; major shareholders
include Flambo International Ltd (45%) and Silchester International
Investors LLP (12%)

## EFB Management Practices

### Primary Utilization Methods

• Composting with POME Integration: GAR operates systematic composting
programs where EFB is combined with treated POME to accelerate
decomposition. The composted material serves as organic fertilizer for
plantation applications.

• Direct Mulching: EFB applied directly to plantation fields as mulch,
gradually decomposing to release nutrients (particularly potassium) and
improve soil structure.

• Biogas Production: As of 2023, GAR operates 7 methane capture
facilities at mills across Central Kalimantan, Jambi, and Riau. Company
committed to expanding to 10 facilities by 2025. These biogas plants can
reduce GHG emissions by 40-55% at equipped mills.

• Precision Agriculture Integration: GAR employs data-driven approaches
to optimize organic amendment application rates.

### Emerging Technologies and Pilot Programs

GAR participates in advanced research programs through partnerships with
Wageningen University & Research (WUR) and IPB University (Institut
Pertanian Bogor) under the SustainPalm initiative. Key developments
include:

• Anaerobic Digestion with EFB/POME Mix: Pilot facilities at SMARTRI
(Sinar Mas Agribusiness Research & Technology Institute) in Libo, near
Pekanbaru

• Digestate Fertilizer Trials: Comparative studies evaluating chemical
fertilizers vs. mulched EFB with POME vs. composted EFB with POME vs.
EFB/POME digestate

• Bio-CNG Production: In 2025, PT SMART Tbk announced plans to produce
Compressed Biogas (Bio-CNG) from POME, supporting company\'s Net Zero
Emissions 2050 target

• Landscape-Level Conservation Integration: GAR works with local
communities, protecting approximately 43,000 ha of forests adjacent to
operations

## PKF/PKS Utilization

• Boiler Fuel Operations: Palm kernel shells (PKS) and mesocarp fiber
serve as primary boiler fuel across GAR\'s mill network, eliminating
dependence on fossil fuels

• Electricity Generation: Biomass-fired cogeneration systems produce
electricity for mill operations, kernel crushing plants, and worker
housing complexes

• PKS Export Market: GAR participates in international PKS trade,
particularly to Japan and South Korea under renewable energy incentive
programs

## Sustainability Framework and Performance

### Certifications and Standards

• RSPO (Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil): Significant portion of
GAR\'s landbank is RSPO-certified

• ISPO (Indonesian Sustainable Palm Oil): Complies with mandatory
Indonesian government sustainability certification

• ISCC (International Sustainability and Carbon Certification): Enables
supply to EU markets requiring sustainability verification under EUDR

### Environmental Performance Metrics

• GHG Emissions Reduction: Methane capture facilities at 7 mills
(expanding to 10) target 40-55% reduction in mill-level emissions.
Company pursuing Net Zero Emissions by 2050

• Water Efficiency: Water intensity for CPO production decreased from
3.96 m³/MT CPO (2022) to 3.85 m³/MT CPO (2023)

• POME Treatment: All mills employ wastewater treatment systems to
reduce BOD and COD levels

• Biodiversity Conservation: BEFTA and RERTA projects with Cambridge and
Southampton universities

### Challenges and Controversies

• Deforestation Allegations: Environmental organizations have documented
forest loss within GAR concession areas, particularly in Central
Kalimantan

• Peatland Development: Historical development of peatlands in Riau and
Kalimantan provinces (\~20,000 ha identified by Greenpeace in Riau)

• Supply Chain Complexity: GAR sources FFB from third-party suppliers,
smallholders, and dealers, making comprehensive traceability challenging

## Strategic Positioning for CFI Engagement

For CFI (Circular Fertiliser Industries), GAR/Sinar Mas represents a
strategically significant potential partner due to:

• Scale of Operations: With 50+ mills processing millions of tonnes of
FFB, GAR generates substantial EFB volumes

• Sustainability Pressure: GAR\'s public sustainability commitments (Net
Zero 2050, NDPE policies, RSPO certification) create strong alignment
with CFI\'s circular economy value proposition

• Research Infrastructure: Existing partnerships with Wageningen and IPB
through SustainPalm program. SMARTRI research facilities provide
potential pilot implementation sites

• Financial Capacity: As major publicly-listed entity with investment
from global institutional investors (BlackRock, Vanguard, State Street),
GAR possesses capital resources for transformative technology adoption

# Detailed Company Profile 2: Wilmar International Limited

## Company Overview

Wilmar International Limited, headquartered in Singapore, stands as
Asia\'s leading agribusiness group and the world\'s largest palm oil
processor. Founded in 1991 by Kuok Khoon Hong and Martua Sitorus, Wilmar
has evolved into a vertically integrated conglomerate spanning the
entire palm oil value chain from cultivation to consumer products. The
company ranks among the largest listed corporations on the Singapore
Exchange and placed 211th in the Fortune Global 500 (2020).

### Operational Scale and Global Presence

• Plantation Operations: Approximately 230,000 hectares of oil palm
plantations across Indonesia, Malaysia, and Africa. Additional 60,000 ha
through joint ventures

• Milling Capacity: 45 company-owned palm oil mills in Indonesia and
Malaysia. Nine Indonesian mills operate as independent facilities
sourcing exclusively from third-party FFB suppliers

• Refining Network: Over 850 mills supply Wilmar refineries across
multiple countries

• Fertilizer Division: Major Indonesian fertilizer player with 1.2
million MT per annum NPK compound fertilizer capacity, plus 100,000 MT
capacity in Sabah

## EFB Management Practices

### Core Utilization Strategies

• Direct Mulching and Organic Fertilizer: Primary EFB management
approach involves returning empty bunches and liquid waste (POME) to
plantations as organic fertilizer

• Composting Operations: Systematic composting programs transform EFB
into stable organic amendments

• Methane Capture at Scale: As of 2023, Wilmar operates 25 methane
capture facilities across Indonesian and Malaysian mills. These biogas
systems can reduce palm oil mill GHG emissions by up to 90%

• Anaerobic Digestion of EFB/POME: Advanced facilities employ
co-digestion of EFB with POME in anaerobic digesters

### Waste Management Infrastructure

• Integrated Waste Recovery Systems: Wilmar mills maintain comprehensive
waste management protocols

• POME Treatment: Wastewater treatment systems at all mills reduce
biological and chemical oxygen demand

• Water Efficiency Targets: 2023 targets to reduce water consumption
intensity to 1.20 m³/MT FFB (Indonesia) and 1.30 m³/MT FFB (Malaysia,
Ghana, Nigeria)

## PKF/PKS Utilization

• Primary Boiler Fuel: Palm fiber and palm kernel shells serve as
primary fuel sources for mill boilers

• Cogeneration Systems: Biomass-fired cogeneration produces both thermal
energy and electrical power

• PKS Export Business: Wilmar participates in substantial PKS trading
operations. Japan alone imported 1.3 million tonnes PKS in 2023, with
Indonesia supplying approximately 75%

## Sustainability Framework and Performance

### Certifications and Standards

• RSPO Membership: Wilmar joined RSPO in 2004. Malaysian upstream
operations fully RSPO-certified. Target for all mills and plantations by
2025

• ISPO Compliance: Meets Indonesian Sustainable Palm Oil mandatory
standards

• ISCC Certification: Enables European market access under EUDR
requirements

### Supply Chain Traceability

• Mill-Level Traceability: Achieved 98.8% traceability to mill level in
2023 (externally verified by Control Union)

• Plantation-Level Traceability: 100% traceability for company-owned
mills; 90.6% for entire supply network (2023). Target: 100% by 2025

• Transparency Initiative: In 2015, Wilmar published online dashboard
with information on all 800+ palm oil suppliers

• NDPE Monitoring: Partnered with Aidenvironment consultancy for
satellite monitoring of suppliers

## Challenges and Controversies

• 2022 Cooking Oil Crisis: During Indonesia\'s cooking oil shortage,
Wilmar executives were convicted of conspiring to redirect palm oil from
domestic market to exports. Master Parulian Tumanggor sentenced to 18
months prison

• 2025 Supreme Court Ruling: Indonesian Supreme Court found Wilmar
guilty of corruption, ordering payment of IDR 11.8 trillion (\~\$907
million USD) in compensation

• Military Land Seizures: Recent Indonesian government crackdown has
scrutinized Wilmar subsidiaries

• Environmental Criticism: In 2012, Newsweek named Wilmar the world\'s
least environmentally friendly company. Norway\'s Government Pension
Fund excluded Wilmar in 2013

## Strategic Positioning for CFI Engagement

### Strategic Advantages

• Unparalleled Scale: With 45 mills and processing capacity from 850+
supply network mills, Wilmar offers access to enormous EFB volumes

• Integrated Fertilizer Business: Wilmar\'s existing 1.2 million MT/year
NPK fertilizer production provides natural synergies with CFI\'s organic
fertilizer value proposition

• Technical Sophistication: 25 methane capture facilities demonstrate
technical capability

• Geographic Reach: Operations spanning multiple Indonesian provinces
enable multi-site pilot programs

### Key Considerations

• Regulatory Risk: Recent Supreme Court ruling (\$907M compensation),
ongoing military investigations create uncertain operating environment

• Reputational Factors: Historical environmental and labor controversies
may impact partnership perceptions

• Supply Chain Complexity: With 850+ mills in supply network, ensuring
consistent EFB quality presents operational challenges

• Competitive Fertilizer Operations: Wilmar\'s existing NPK fertilizer
business could view protein-enriched organic fertilizer as competitive
rather than complementary

# COMPLIANCE TIERS & MARKET IMPLICATIONS

**TIER 1: ADVANCED/COMPLIANT (Ready for Dec 30, 2024 EUDR deadline) -- 2
companies**

✓ Sinar Mas/SMART (GAR) -- 536,234 ha: 100% deforestation-free; due
diligence & segregation verified; EU reporting: Full compliance
announced

✓ Musim Mas -- 124,464 ha: NDPE verified; 100% segregation procedures;
smallholder programme active; EU reporting: Ready for Dec 30, 2024

**TIER 2: STRONG/COMPLIANT (Own operations) -- 2 companies**

✓ First Resources -- 215,128 ha: 84% own+plasma operations EUDR-ready;
updated supplier due diligence; ISCC waste residues certified

✓ Wilmar International -- 151,698 ha: NDPE compliant for own
plantations; smallholder engagement ongoing (80% ISPO, 38% RSPO)

**TIER 3: MODERATE/EMERGING CLARITY -- 4 companies**

⚠ Asian Agri, DSNG, Triputra Agro Persada, Bumitama Agri -- 621,816 ha
combined: RSPO/ISCC certified but limited EUDR-specific public
disclosure. Risk: Documentation gaps may delay EU market access in 2026

**TIER 4: CRITICAL HIGH RISK -- 3 companies**

✗ Astra Agro Lestari -- 284,831 ha: CRITICAL: Alleged permitting
violations; \~1,100 ha in protected forest zones. FoE report: 3
subsidiaries lack HGU permits. EU RISK: Potential market block; EU law
enforcement investigation flagged. Estimated impact: 1.2 million tonnes
annual FFB at risk

✗ PTPN III (PalmCo) -- 586,000 ha (LARGEST PRODUCER): CRITICAL:
State-owned; RSPO certification in progress; no clear 2026 compliance
roadmap. Government data systems: Limited public transparency. Estimated
impact: 5.3 million tonnes FFB (largest vulnerability in industry)

✗ Sampoerna Agro -- 128,000 ha: RSPO member but minimal EUDR
documentation publicly available. Estimated impact: 0.55 million tonnes
FFB at potential supply chain risk

