## *EUDR ensures materials are traceable and deforestation-free. CSRD is the next logical step --- requiring companies to report, verify, and disclose that traceability as part of their sustainability performance.*

## Key Findings

• Only 2 companies (Sinar Mas, Musim Mas) have transparent, verified
EUDR compliance for full market access

• 4 companies (Asian Agri, DSNG, Triputra, Bumitama) have documentation
gaps that may delay EU market entry

• 3 companies (Astra, Sampoerna, PTPN III) face critical compliance
risks; Astra under active EU law enforcement investigation

• PTPN III, Indonesia\'s largest producer, has no published EUDR roadmap
despite accounting for 5.3M tonnes annual FFB

# CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS

## Industry Landscape Summary

The Indonesian palm oil industry generates approximately 28-31 million
tonnes of EFB annually from 53+ million tonnes of CPO production. While
traditional mulching remains dominant (70%+ of mills), progressive
companies increasingly adopt advanced waste valorization:

• Composting with POME co-treatment improves nutrient availability and
meets Indonesian fertilizer standards (SNI 19-7030-2004)

• Methane capture facilities at 25-50 mills across major producers
reduce emissions 40-90% while generating renewable electricity

• Emerging technologies include mushroom cultivation (47-282 kg per
tonne EFB), bio-oil production, bioethanol via glucose extraction, and
pelletization for export

• PKS/PKF universally utilized for mill energy self-sufficiency, with
PKS export market to Japan/Korea representing high-value revenue stream
(\$20-35/tonne)

## CFI Market Entry Opportunities

For Circular Fertiliser Industries deploying Black Soldier Fly (BSF)
bioconversion technology, the Indonesian palm oil sector offers
compelling value propositions:

### Value Proposition Elements

• Waste Volume and Consistency: Guaranteed feedstock supply at scale
(each 60-ton/hour mill produces 1.5 MW equivalent EFB, or \~25,000
tonnes annually). Year-round tropical production ensures continuous BSF
colony operations

• Regulatory Drivers: EU Deforestation Regulation (EUDR, effective Jan
2025) pressures companies to demonstrate sustainable, zero-waste
operations. Carbon credit opportunities via ACM0022 methodology
incentivize methane-free organic matter treatment

• Protein Market: Indonesia imports significant DAP/TSP fertilizers and
animal feed proteins. CFI\'s protein-enriched frass and insect meal
offer import substitution opportunity

• Circular Economy Alignment: Palm companies increasingly adopt
closed-loop nutrient management. BSF technology returning high-quality
organic fertilizer with 12-15% protein content aligns with precision
agriculture initiatives

## Recommended Target Companies (Priority Ranking)

### 1. Golden Agri Resources (GAR) / Sinar Mas - HIGHEST PRIORITY

• Rationale: Active sustainability research partnerships (Wageningen,
IPB), existing pilot facilities (SMARTRI), biogas expansion program
(7→10 mills), Net Zero 2050 commitment

• Scale: 50+ mills, 450,000 ha, substantial EFB volumes

• Entry Point: Approach through SustainPalm program collaboration,
propose BSF pilot at SMARTRI research facility

### 2. Asian Agri / Royal Golden Eagle - HIGH PRIORITY

• Rationale: 11 biogas plants demonstrate technical sophistication, 2030
sustainability targets (AsianAgri2030) with climate-positive
commitments, mushroom cultivation trials indicate openness to biological
waste treatment

• Scale: 23-28 mills, 160,000 ha, primarily Sumatra

• Entry Point: Position BSF as complementary to biogas (pre-treatment
increasing methane yields), emphasize protein value for smallholder
partnerships

### 3. Astra Agro Lestari - MODERATE PRIORITY

• Rationale: 5-Year Sustainability Action Plan (2021-2025), ISPO
certification focus, but limited current biogas adoption creates
technology gap that BSF could fill

• Scale: 25-30 mills, 300,000 ha across Sumatra, Kalimantan, Sulawesi

• Entry Point: Emphasize lower capital intensity vs. methane capture,
faster ROI, organic fertilizer premium pricing potential

• Considerations: Ongoing land conflict controversies in Sulawesi may
impact partnership reputational aspects

### 4. Wilmar International - MODERATE-LOW PRIORITY

• Rationale: Largest scale (45 mills, 850+ supplier network), existing
fertilizer business provides market access, 25 methane capture
facilities show technical capacity

• Considerations: Recent legal challenges (\$907M Supreme Court ruling,
ongoing government investigations), competitive fertilizer division,
complex supply chain creates implementation challenges

• Entry Point: Target independent mills sourcing only from third
parties, propose pilot at 1-2 mills to demonstrate value before broader
discussions

