**11.1 Carbon Certification Overview -- What Is Required**

**Why Certification Matters**

CFI\'s emissions avoidance (151,200 tCO₂e/year) has no monetary value
without third-party validation. Verra carbon credits are the globally
recognized standard for voluntary carbon market trading. The
certification process ensures additionality (project would not occur
without carbon revenue, demonstrated via financial models), baseline
accuracy (emissions avoided calculated using IPCC-validated
methodologies under ACM0022), monitoring rigor (measurement systems
including meters, lab analysis, and protocols track actual emissions
reduction), and verification integrity (independent auditors validate
data annually before credit issuance).

**Revenue Potential**

At current voluntary carbon market pricing, CFI\'s baseline projection
is 151,200 tCO₂e/year × \$15--25/tCO₂e = \$2.27--3.78 million annually.
The 10-year revenue stream totals \$22.7--37.8 million (before
certification costs, after M&V ongoing). Net present value after
certification reaches \$20.1--34.2 million (assuming 7% discount rate,
deducting all certification and ongoing costs).

**11.2 Month-by-Month Cost Breakdown -- 24-Month Timeline**

**Phase 1: Project Scoping (Months 0--2) -- \$18,000--\$25,000**

This phase encompasses the feasibility study to determine if the project
is viable economically and technically, PIN (Project Idea Note)
preparation as a 5--10 page overview for Verra pre-screening,
methodology selection confirmation for ACM0022 (Alternative Waste
Treatment) applicability assessment, and consultant team assembly with
Verra-accredited consultants and methodology experts.

Funding typically comes from CFI or a co-investment partner such as
Nestlé or Musim Mas. Deliverables include an approved PIN from Verra
(informal approval with approximately 2--4 weeks turnaround) and a
methodology scoping document confirming ACM0022 applicability.

Cost drivers include consultant hourly rates of \$80--150/hr (200--250
hours), optional travel for site assessment (\$2,000--5,000), and PIN
document preparation (\$1,000--3,000).

**Phase 2: Methodology & PDD Drafting (Months 2--6) --
\$35,000--\$50,000**

This phase involves PDD (Project Design Document) drafting as a 50--100
page technical document detailing project design, baseline scenario,
additionality, and monitoring plan. IPCC model setup validates waste
inputs, DOC, MCF factors, and GWP calculations. Stakeholder consultation
planning identifies affected communities and prepares the consultation
strategy. Registry pre-listing establishes informal communication with
Verra to confirm the listing process.

Funding comes from CFI or a co-investor, potentially split with an ERPA
sponsor if pre-sales are underway. Deliverables include a draft PDD
ready for internal review and stakeholder consultation, plus validated
baseline calculations and emissions projections.

Cost drivers include PDD consulting with a Verra-experienced consultant
at \$100--150/hr (300--400 hours) totaling \$30,000--60,000, methodology
specialist review at \$2,000--5,000, stakeholder consultation prep at
\$2,000--3,000, and registry pre-listing admin at \$1,000--2,000.

A financing opportunity arises in Months 4--5: if strong market interest
from carbon buyers exists, signing an ERPA (Emissions Reduction Purchase
Agreement) for 10--30% upfront payment becomes viable. Example
calculation: 0.10 × 151,200 tCO₂e/yr × \$20/tCO₂e = \$302,400 (if 10%
Year 1 purchase at \$20). This can offset Months 6--10 costs entirely.

**Phase 3: Validation Preparation & Stakeholder Consultation (Months
6--10) -- \$46,000--\$65,000**

This phase includes final PDD edits based on stakeholder feedback
(community consultation, local government letters), scheduling
validation audits with an independent VVB (Validating & Verification
Body, Verra-accredited), registry fees where Verra charges
\$5,000--10,000 for listing and ongoing account maintenance, and
documentation dossier preparation covering permits, financial models,
and technical specs.

Funding comes from CFI or a co-investor, with ERPA upfront able to
defray costs. Deliverables include a PDD fully finalized and approved
for VVB audit, plus an established Verra registry account with project
listed.

Cost drivers include VVB validation audit (3--5 days onsite) at
\$20,000--35,000, PDD final edits and compilation at \$5,000--8,000,
Verra registry fees at \$5,000--10,000, stakeholder documentation at
\$2,000--5,000, and travel for VVB site visit and consultant at
\$10,000--15,000.

**Phase 4: MRV Setup (Months 10--14) -- \$40,000--\$62,000**

This phase covers monitoring equipment installation including flow
meters (waste input), moisture sensors, lab scales, and temperature
sensors. Lab protocols are established for waste composition analysis,
carbon content verification, and quality assurance. Staff training
prepares technicians on monitoring procedures, data recording, and
sample handling. Registration with Verra formally registers the project
as the final milestone before verification audits begin.

Funding comes from CFI as essential infrastructure investment.
Deliverables include fully operational and calibrated monitoring systems
plus official project registration confirmation from Verra.

Cost drivers include equipment (meters, sensors, scales, lab gear) at
\$15,000--25,000, lab protocol development and QA setup at
\$5,000--8,000, staff training (2--3 staff, 20--30 hours each) at
\$3,000--5,000, calibration and startup at \$5,000--8,000, registration
admin fees at \$3,000--5,000, documentation and manuals at
\$2,000--3,000, and travel for training and consultant follow-up at
\$2,000--5,000.

**Phase 5: Pre-Verification Readiness & Verification Audit (Months
14--22) -- \$38,000--\$58,000**

This phase encompasses data collection and QA (Months 14--18) where 4
months of monitoring data is compiled, errors checked, and gaps
identified. Verification audit planning (Months 16--18) schedules VVB
audit dates and confirms audit scope. Verification fieldwork (Months
18--20) involves the VVB team visiting the facility, reviewing records,
interviewing staff, and validating monitoring equipment. Issuance fees
and final documentation (Months 20--22) completes Verra\'s processing
for credit issuance.

Funding comes from CFI or a co-investor, with ERPA potentially providing
funding. Deliverables include a monitoring report approved by VVB,
carbon credits issued to CFI account (approximately 151,200 credits for
Year 1), and credits ready for sale on the secondary market.

Cost drivers include verification audit (VVB) at \$15,000--25,000, data
QA and report prep at \$5,000--10,000, issuance fees (Verra,
approximately \$0.02--0.05/credit) at \$3,000--7,500, travel for VVB
audit at \$5,000--10,000, legal/admin for credit issuance at
\$2,000--5,000, and contingency for data gaps and re-testing at
\$3,000--5,000.

**Phase 6: Post-Issuance & Handover (Months 22--24) --
\$2,000--\$3,000**

This phase includes final reporting to Verra, credit transfer to carbon
brokerage or direct buyers, and handover of monitoring protocols and
data to the ongoing M&V team. Cost drivers include final documentation
at \$1,000--2,000 and admin processing at \$1,000--1,500.

**11.3 Detailed Cost Categories**

**Consultant & Professional Services**

Verra-accredited consultant services for PDD drafting and monitoring
plan run at \$100--150/hr with 600--800 hours required across 24 months,
totaling \$60,000--120,000.

VVB (Validation & Verification) services include the validation audit at
\$20,000--35,000 (Months 6--10) and verification audit at
\$15,000--25,000 (Months 18--20), subtotaling \$35,000--60,000.

Methodology specialist services for IPCC calculations and baseline run
at \$120--180/hr with 50--100 hours required, subtotaling
\$6,000--18,000.

Total consulting costs range from \$101,000--198,000, representing
roughly 55--65% of total investment.

**Registry & Formal Fees**

Verra registration includes project listing at \$5,000--10,000, annual
account maintenance at \$2,000--3,000/yr (included in M&V budget), and
issuance processing at \$0.02--0.05/credit yielding \$3,000--7,500 for
151,200 credits. Total registry costs range from \$8,000--17,500.

**Equipment & Monitoring Setup**

Flow meters and sensors include a waste input meter at \$3,000--5,000,
moisture sensor at \$1,000--2,000, and temperature probe at
\$500--1,000, subtotaling \$4,500--8,000.

Lab equipment (scales, centrifuge, analytical gear) includes a precision
lab scale at \$2,000--4,000, sample prep equipment at \$2,000--3,000,
and pH/conductivity meter at \$1,000--2,000, subtotaling \$5,000--9,000.

Calibration and QA subtotals \$5,000--8,000. Total equipment costs range
from \$14,500--25,000, representing roughly 8--10% of total investment.

**Travel & Site Logistics**

Consultant travel (site visits, training) includes Indonesia flights
(Asia-US round trip) at \$1,000--1,500 per trip, ground transport and
hotel at \$2,000--4,000 per trip, with an estimated 8--10 trips over 24
months, subtotaling \$24,000--55,000.

VVB auditor travel is included in VVB audit fees (typically
\$20,000--35,000 for validation, \$15,000--25,000 for verification).
Total travel costs range from \$24,000--55,000, representing roughly
13--21% of total investment.

**Stakeholder Consultation & Permits**

Community consultation including information sessions and documentation
costs \$3,000--5,000. Government and regulatory permits including
environmental permits and certificates cost \$1,000--3,000. Total
stakeholder costs range from \$4,000--8,000.

**11.4 ERPA Upfront Financing Strategy**

**How ERPAs Help CFI**

An ERPA (Emissions Reduction Purchase Agreement) is a forward contract
between CFI and a carbon buyer (corporation, carbon fund, trader). The
buyer commits to purchasing Year 1+ carbon credits at an agreed price.

Typical ERPA structure includes an upfront payment of 10--30% of Year 1
credits at contract signing (Months 4--6, during PDD finalization).
Example calculation: 151,200 tCO₂e/yr × 20% upfront × \$20/tCO₂e =
\$604,800 upfront payment. Delivery of the remaining 70--90% is paid
upon credit delivery after the verification audit.

**CFI Cost Coverage Timeline with ERPA**

Scenario: ERPA signed Month 5, 20% upfront at \$20/tCO₂e. ERPA upfront
received (Month 5): \$604,800. Months 0--5 costs incurred:
\$53,000--75,000. Months 6--24 costs projected: \$124,000--185,000.
Total costs: \$177,000--260,000.

ERPA upfront (\$604,800) covers 100% of Months 0--10 costs
(approximately \$100,000--140,000) plus partial funding of Months 10--24
(approximately \$77,000--120,000). This leaves CFI with a net positive
cash position of \$184,000--404,000 after all costs.

**ERPA Risk & Additionality**

Additionality requirement: To qualify for carbon credits, CFI must
demonstrate the project wouldn\'t happen without carbon revenue. ERPA
upfront strengthens additionality by proving market demand and forward
revenue.

Market buyers for CFI include corporate sustainability teams (Nestlé,
AAK, Musim Mas carbon commitments), impact funds (Asian carbon funds,
development finance institutions), carbon traders seeking high-quality
avoided emissions credits, and ESG portfolios allocating capital to
Scope 3 supply chain decarbonization.

