**SECTION 12. SALES & OFFTAKE STRATEGY**

This section provides comprehensive strategic guidance for CFI\'s market
positioning, covering both government subsidy channels through Pupuk
Indonesia and premium export markets through international partnerships
with Yara and ICL.

**12.1 PARTNERING WITH PUPUK INDONESIA FOR SUBSIDY CHANNELS**

Pupuk Indonesia (the state-owned holding company for fertilizer
producers) controls Indonesia\'s subsidized fertilizer distribution,
which includes urea, NPK blends (even crop-specific formulas like a
cocoa NPK), and organic fertilizers. To tap into this channel, CFI can
consider the following approaches:

**12.1.1 Toll Manufacturing under Pupuk Indonesia\'s Brand**

CFI could produce organo-mineral fertilizer meeting the government\'s
SNI standards and subsidy specifications, then package it under Pupuk
Indonesia\'s unified subsidized brand (they now use a single brand for
all subsidized urea, NPK, and organic fertilizers).

This kind of \"tolling\" arrangement has precedent -- e.g. Petrokimia
Gresik\'s Petroganik organic fertilizer was produced by partnering with
local suppliers (farm co-ops) and then standardized and sold under
Petrokimia\'s brand. CFI could similarly supply organo-mineral
fertilizer to a Pupuk Indonesia subsidiary (like Pupuk Kaltim in East
Kalimantan) to be distributed as part of the subsidized quota.

**This gives CFI access to a guaranteed market (smallholder rice, corn,
coffee, etc.) while leveraging Pupuk Indonesia\'s extensive distribution
network.**

**12.1.2 Co-Branding or Joint Ventures**

Alternatively, CFI might form a joint venture or co-branding deal with
Pupuk Indonesia for a new line of organo-mineral products. For instance,
a \"Pupuk Indonesia -- CFI Organik\" blend could be introduced for
subsidized programs targeting soil health.

Given the government\'s push for regenerative practices and the
inclusion of organic fertilizer in the subsidy scheme, Pupuk Indonesia
may welcome partnerships that bolster supply. CFI\'s value proposition
would be its unique organo-mineral formulation that improves soil
organic matter (aligning with sustainable agriculture goals) while still
providing NPK nutrients.

**12.1.3 Navigating Subsidy Requirements**

CFI must ensure the product meets subsidy specs (nutrient content,
physical form, SNI certification, etc.) and competitive pricing.
Subsidized prices are fixed low; however, the government often
compensates producers. CFI might receive a manufacturing fee or
cost-plus payment under contract.

The upside is volume: Pupuk Indonesia distributed \~7.5 million tons of
subsidized fertilizer in 2024, so even a small allocation (for example,
an organic blend for coffee or sugarcane, which are now prioritized
crops) could mean significant tonnage. Close coordination with the
Ministry of Agriculture would be needed to get CFI\'s product included
in the subsidy program.

**12.1.4 Why Pupuk Indonesia Might Be Interested**

The government has removed oil palm from subsidy and is encouraging
organic soil amendments. Also, coffee and cocoa are now included for
subsidies, indicating a demand for specialized fertilizers. CFI\'s
organo-mineral pellets could help Pupuk Indonesia fulfill these policy
goals by providing a fertilizer that boosts yields and soil health.

If structured as a toll manufacture, Pupuk Indonesia can claim the
product under its umbrella without large capital investment in new
factories. This mirrors earlier solutions where big fertilizer companies
partnered with small producers to meet organic fertilizer targets.

**12.2 FREE MARKET POSITIONING (NON-SUBSIDIZED)**

Outside the regulated subsidy market, CFI can target higher-value
channels through offtake agreements or exports:

**12.2.1 Ex-factory Pricing and Offtake Partnership with Yara or ICL**

Major international fertilizer companies are increasingly interested in
organic-based or organo-mineral fertilizers. Yara, for example, launched
its YaraSuna™ organic-based fertilizer line in 2024, and ICL has
developed an organo-mineral range (Gronamic) combining organic nutrients
with their minerals.

**CFI could position itself as a contract manufacturer for these
companies in Southeast Asia. For instance, Yara might co-brand and
purchase CFI\'s product to include in their portfolio for Asia (saving
them shipping costs from Europe).**

If CFI can meet Yara\'s specs (nutrient content, \~30% organic C,
micropellet form, free of contaminants), Yara could offtake volumes to
sell under YaraSuna branding in regional markets. Similarly, ICL could
source product for markets like turf, plantation crops, or organic
farming segments.

An offtake deal would provide CFI a stable demand at an agreed price
(likely indexed to nutrient content). These firms emphasize quality and
consistency -- CFI would need robust QA/QC to ensure each batch meets
international standards (heavy metal limits, uniform granule size,
etc.).

**12.2.2 Export to Premium Markets (Japan, South Korea) -- CIF
\$300-400/ton**

Japan and Korea have advanced agriculture sectors with niches that pay
premium for organic or sustainable inputs. Indonesia already exports
organic fertilizers to Japan, Korea, and regional neighbors.

CFI\'s organo-mineral pellets could appeal to high-value crop growers
(tea, horticulture, golf courses, etc.) in those countries. For example,
Japanese tea farmers or Korean ginseng growers might pay extra for a
fertilizer that is partly organic yet nutrient-rich, to meet both yield
and environmental goals.

To succeed here, CFI should obtain relevant certifications:

• Japan Organic Agriculture Standard (JAS) if applicable\
• OMRI listing for organic use\
• Product positioning highlighting recycled organic matter and mineral
nutrients

These markets often prefer consistent, bulk loose shipments for large
farms or plantations. CFI could ship in bulk (loose) or in big bags to
importers, reducing packaging costs.

**12.2.3 Organo-Mineral Mix FOB Pricing (\$300-450/ton)**

*Mixing cost: \$69 in CFI factory for the 6-5-5 NPK synthetic addition.*

While exact prices require negotiation, CFI must remain competitive
against other sources. European retail prices for organo-mineral NPK
fertilizers give a reference point --

**CFI\'s East Kalimantan location means additional freight to overseas
markets, so to entice offtakers, the ex-factory price might need to be
in the few-hundreds of USD per ton range.**

**12.3 YARA\'S ORGANO-MINERAL LINE AND COMMON NPK RATIOS**

To guide CFI\'s product development, it\'s useful to examine Yara\'s
organo-mineral fertilizer formulas. Yara\'s new line (YaraSuna™)
contains six products, each starting with \"R\" for \"Regenerative\".
Notably, three are pure organic or soil amendments, and three are
organo-mineral NPK fertilizers.

CFI can formulate blends similar to the organo-mineral ones by adding
mineral nutrients to its organic base.

**Table 93: YaraSuna Organically-Enhanced Fertilizers**

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
