formulated as 2-4 mm micropellets for uniform spreading.*

**12.3.1 Most-Sold NPK Ratio Analysis**

In Yara\'s experience, balanced NPK formulas are popular. Globally, a
15-15-15 NPK compound is a common \"all-purpose\" fertilizer -- YaraMila
15-15-15 is cited as suitable even for oil palm nurseries.

For higher-value crops (oil palm, coffee, fruits), a high-K formula like
6-5-10 (Riflora) or custom blends (e.g. 12-12-17-2MgO) would be in
demand. In Indonesia, oil palm is no longer subsidized, so an
organo-mineral with high K could sell well to plantations.

**Expected Best-Sellers for CFI:**

• High-K formulas: Best for plantation segment (palm, coffee)\
• Balanced NPK (15-15-15 or 12-12-12): Volume driver for general use

**12.4 PREFERRED FERTILIZER FORM: PELLETIZING VS GRANULATION**

When producing organo-mineral blends, pelletized form is preferred over
traditional granules. Yara specifically chose a micro-pellet (1--4 mm)
format for YaraSuna, rather than trying to granulate like a purely
mineral fertilizer.

**12.4.1 Why Pelletizing Is Superior**

The pellet approach allows a high organic matter content (\~30%) to be
combined with mineral nutrients and still form a stable product. Key
advantages:

• Cold-pressing or extrusion preserves organic nutrients and microbes\
• Yara avoids high-temperature drying to keep biology alive\
• Resulting pellets are uniform and free-flowing\
• Easy to spread with conventional equipment\
• Each pellet delivers consistent NPK dose

**12.4.2 Granulation Limitations**

Granulation (like that used for mineral NPKs) is less suitable because
the organic components don\'t melt or bind the way salts do. Instead,
pelletizing with a binder (or using the natural fiber in manure) yields
a robust granule.

Yara\'s micropellets are evidence that pelletizing is the best practice
for organo-mineral products -- it ensures \"convenient spreading\" and
integration into farmers\' existing practice. CFI should likewise
produce a pelletized fertilizer.

**Packaging Options:**

• 25 kg bags for retail/smallholder markets\
• 500 kg big bags for commercial buyers\
• Bulk loose shipments (1-ton bags or bulk containers) for
plantation-scale buyers

**12.5 STRATEGIC SUMMARY**

**CFI\'s strategy should be two-pronged:**

**Strategy 1: Inside Indonesia\'s Subsidy System**

Partner with Pupuk Indonesia to supply organo-mineral fertilizer
(leveraging toll manufacturing or co-branding to reach millions of small
farmers in rice, corn, coffee sectors).

• Access to 7.5 million ton distribution network\
• Government compensation for subsidized pricing\
• Priority crops: coffee, cocoa, sugarcane (now included in subsidy)\
• Volume guarantee through Pupuk Indonesia contracts

**Strategy 2: Outside the Subsidy (Premium Markets)**

Align with global players like Yara or ICL for offtake agreements and
target export markets where sustainable fertilizers fetch a premium.

• Yara/ICL contract manufacturing: \$300-450/ton FOB\
• Japan/Korea premium exports: CIF \$300-400/ton\
• Certifications: JAS, OMRI for market access\
• QA/QC systems for international standards compliance

**Product Positioning Recommendations**

Focus on formulas proven by Yara\'s research -- especially high-K grades
for oil palm and coffee, and balanced grades for staples -- all
delivered in pellet form for ease of use.

**By doing so, CFI can command a fair ex-factory price based on nutrient
value (with indications that a product similar to YaraSuna could
wholesale in the mid-hundreds USD/ton range) while differentiating
itself as a provider of both crop nutrition and soil health.**

This combination of strategic partnerships and right product mix will
position CFI strongly in the evolving fertilizer market.

