**SECTION 13. INDONESIA PERMITS FOR CFI FACILITY**

This section provides a chronological permitting / legal framework
timeline relevant to establishing and operating a Black Soldier Fly
(BSF) waste-valorization facility on Indonesian palm plantations. It
focuses on the official enactment dates of national laws and regulations
governing:

\(a\) Business establishment & licensing (OSS risk-based system)\
(b) Environmental approvals (AMDAL / UKL-UPL / SPPL)\
(c) Waste management\
(d) Subsequent amendments up to mid-2025

**KEY TAKEAWAYS**

**1. No BSF-specific permit -- comply with waste, environmental, and
risk-based business licensing layers (now under GR 28/2025).**

**2. Environmental document tier (UKL-UPL or SPPL) is the pivotal step
for most medium-scale BSF valorization (AMDAL only if crossing higher
impact thresholds).**

**3. All applications flow through OSS RBA, integrating spatial,
environmental, and building approvals; earlier licenses remain valid
under successive legal updates.**

**4. Verify KBLI code selection early (organic waste treatment /
fertilizer production) to ensure correct risk classification.**

**13.1 CORE WASTE MANAGEMENT LAW**

**Law No. 18 of 2008 on Waste Management**

Adopted/promulgated: 7 May 2008

This law establishes national principles, government responsibilities,
and the legal basis for integrated waste handling. Non-hazardous
plantation residues like EFB/PKS fall under this general regime.

**13.2 OMNIBUS JOB CREATION REFORM**

**Law No. 11/2020 -- Risk-Based Licensing Foundation**

The Job Creation Bill was passed 5 October 2020 and enacted
(promulgated) 2 November 2020 as Law No. 11/2020, introducing reforms
that mandate risk-based business licensing later implemented through
Government Regulations and OSS system upgrades.

This sets the stage for risk classification and streamlined licensing
relevant to new BSF entities (e.g., obtaining NIB, location conformity,
environmental approval).

**Perppu 2/2022 and Law 6/2023 -- Continuity Assured**

Following constitutional review, Government Regulation in Lieu of Law
(Perppu) No. 2/2022 dated 30 December 2022 replaced Law 11/2020, keeping
existing licenses valid and ensuring continuity of previously issued
permits.

Law No. 6 of 2023 (31 March 2023) converted Perppu 2/2022 into permanent
law, reaffirming the risk-based licensing framework continuity --
meaning no re-issuance required solely due to legal form changes for
existing BSF operations.

**13.3 ENVIRONMENTAL APPROVALS FRAMEWORK**

**GR 22/2021 -- Environmental Protection & Management**

Enacted: 2 February 2021

This Government Regulation defines environmental approvals and
integrates them with risk-based licensing (AMDAL, UKL-UPL, SPPL
pathways) -- critical for siting a BSF waste processing facility.

**PermenLHK 4/2021 -- Activities Requiring AMDAL/UKL-UPL/SPPL**

Effective: 1 April 2021

Minister of Environment & Forestry Regulation No. 4/2021 lists
business/activity categories that must secure an AMDAL, UKL-UPL, or (for
lowest impacts) submit an SPPL.

**BSF waste bioconversion (medium scale) typically falls below AMDAL
thresholds, thus needing UKL-UPL or SPPL depending on scale and KBLI
classification.**

**Criteria for UKL-UPL vs SPPL**

• UKL-UPL: Required for activities without \"significant\" impact\
• SPPL: For lowest-risk micro/small operations\
\
This guides which environmental document a BSF facility must file before
or during OSS submission.

**13.4 OSS RBA LICENSING SYSTEM**

**Platform Launch -- 9 August 2021**

The OSS RBA (Online Single Submission -- Risk Based Approach) platform
was launched 9 August 2021, operationalizing electronic risk-based
licensing (obtaining NIB, environmental approval integration, and
subsequent sectoral licenses) -- now the portal through which a BSF
entity secures foundational permits.

**Current Framework under GR 28/2025**

**Effective: 5 June 2025**

Government Regulation (GR) No. 28/2025 replaces GR 5/2021, refining
transparency and requiring all licensing components (KKPR spatial
conformity, environmental approvals, building permits PBG & SLF) to flow
through OSS.

**BSF projects initiated now must align with GR 28/2025 standards.**

**13.5 PRACTICAL LICENSING SEQUENCE**

**Six-Step Process for CFI Facility (Post-June 2025)**

**Under the post-June 2025 regime, the licensing sequence is:**

Step 1: Prepare KBLI classification (likely under organic waste
processing / fertilizer production codes)

Step 2: Secure Spatial Suitability (KKPR)

Step 3: Determine environmental document tier (AMDAL vs UKL-UPL vs SPPL)
and submit via OSS

Step 4: Obtain NIB (functions as general business license)

Step 5: Complete sectoral standards/statements required for medium-risk
classification (sanitation, waste handling procedures) inside OSS RBA

Step 6: Apply for building permit (PBG) & SLF, all per updated GR
28/2025 integrated process

**KBLI Code Selection**

Verify KBLI code selection early to ensure correct risk classification
and required standards filings under the RBA system. Likely codes:

• Organic waste treatment codes\
• Fertilizer production codes\
• Waste valorization / processing codes

**13.6 BSF-SPECIFIC CONSIDERATIONS**

**General Regime Compliance**

**There is no single national BSF-exclusive permit; operations rely on
general waste management, environmental approval, and risk-based
business licensing.**

Small/community BSF initiatives often proceed without additional local
discretionary permits beyond those frameworks, reflecting practical
uptake of maggot (larva) cultivation for organic waste reduction.

**Export/Market Access Considerations**

For ambitions to export BSF derivative products (meal, oil, fertilizer),
additional approvals may be required:

• Feed permits for animal feed applications\
• Export permits for international markets\
• EU market access approvals (Indonesian authorities working to broaden
permissions)

