**SECTION 14. CFI EXIT SCENARIO**

**CFI as a \$300 Million Platform: Strategic Value Memo**

CFI has proven its core business model with high-margin
waste-to-fertilizer hubs using a hybrid Infrastructure-as-a-Service +
Take-or-Pay Offtake model. CFI has turned underperforming pilots into a
scalable, replicable platform -- each site now de-risked with locked-in
feedstock and offtake agreements.

**14.1 STRATEGIC VALUE BEYOND THE NUMBERS**

CFI\'s true value lies not in its current revenue but in its replicable
and capital-light model. With dozens of potential sites in Indonesia
alone a strategic acquirer doesn\'t just buy today\'s EBITDA -- they buy

• A proven playbook for rapid site deployment\
• Locked-in feedstock partnerships with major palm/shrimp players\
• A ready-made operational team and SOP library\
• Carbon credit pipeline (151,200 tCO₂e/year per site)\
• First-mover advantage in Indonesian circular agriculture

**14.1.1 Proven Business Model**

CFI has demonstrated the ability to convert waste streams into premium
fertilizer products with:

• High-margin operations (EBITDA margins \>40%)\
• Scalable infrastructure approach\
• Take-or-Pay offtake agreements\
• Integrated carbon credit revenue streams

**14.1.2 Replicable Platform Characteristics**

The platform is designed for rapid replication across Indonesia\'s palm,
shrimp, and coffee sectors:

• Standardized facility design and construction\
• Proven supplier relationships\
• Operational playbook and SOPs\
• Training programs for local teams\
• Regulatory pathway established (Section 14)

**14.2 WHY A STRATEGIC BUYER PAYS MORE**

**14.2.1 De-Risked Platform Value**

**Strategic buyers pay a premium for de-risked platforms:**

• Platform is de-risked: proven margins, customer stickiness,
operational playbook\
• Multi-site rollout can be financed against contracted revenues\
• Carbon credits add incremental value (and align with ESG mandates)\
• Strategic acquirer (Yara, Wilmar, Cargill) avoids 2--3 years of pilot
risk

**14.2.2 Multi-Site Rollout Economics**

Each additional site leverages the existing platform infrastructure:

• Site 1 CAPEX: \$2.5M (includes R&D, regulatory, initial setup)\
• Sites 2-10 CAPEX: \$1.8M each (standardized deployment)\
• Sites 11-30 CAPEX: \$1.5M each (economies of scale)\
• Total 30-site deployment: \~\$50M for \~\$300M enterprise value

**14.2.3 Strategic Acquirer Premium Drivers**

Strategic acquirers value CFI for multiple synergies:

• Yara/ICL: Access to organic fertilizer production at scale\
• Wilmar/Cargill: Palm waste valorization and sustainability
credentials\
• Nestlé/Unilever: Supply chain decarbonization (Scope 3)\
• Carbon credit buyers: Verified emissions reduction pipeline\
• Impact investors: Circular economy platform with measurable outcomes

**14.3 VALUATION FRAMEWORK**

**14.3.1 Current Financial Metrics**

**CFI\'s current financials justify baseline valuation:**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Metric**              **Multiple Range**      **Valuation Range**
  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------
  EV/Sales (on \$23.4M)   6--8×                   \$140M--\$187M

  EV/EBITDA (on \$11.4M)  12--15×                 \$137M--\$171M

  DCF (7-year, 12% WACC)  ---                     \$150M--\$180M

  Baseline Valuation      ---                     \$137M--\$187M
  Range                                           
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

**14.3.2 Platform Premium Valuation**

**If CFI is positioned as a scalable platform:**

• Strategic buyer prices on 20--30 facility potential\
• Platform premium: 1.5--2.0× baseline valuation\
• Implied valuation: \$200M--\$300M+

**14.4.2 Strategic Buyer Pricing Model**

**Strategic buyers price on platform potential, not current EBITDA:**

• 30-site potential × \$8M average revenue = \$240M revenue platform\
• At 8× EV/Sales = \$300M+ enterprise value\
• At 40% EBITDA margin × 12× multiple = \$288M enterprise value\
• Platform premium justified by de-risked expansion path

**14.5 PLATFORM-LED EXIT VALUE**

**14.5.1 CFI Differentiation**

**CFI is not a commodity BSF operator -- it is a high-growth platform
company that monetizes waste conversion, soil health, and carbon credits
across Indonesia\'s largest agricultural sectors.**

Key differentiators:

• First-mover advantage in Indonesian circular agriculture\
• Integrated business model (waste + fertilizer + carbon)\
• Strategic partnerships with palm/shrimp majors\
• Regulatory pathway established\
• Proven unit economics across multiple sites

**14.5.2 Exit Value Range**

**Based on platform positioning and strategic buyer interest:**

• Financial Buyer (PE): \$140M--\$180M (current metrics)\
• Strategic Buyer (Yara/Cargill): \$200M--\$250M (synergy premium)\
• Platform Buyer (full rollout): \$250M--\$300M+ (platform value)

**14.6 CONCLUSION**

**Platform-Led Exit Value Summary**

CFI is positioned as a high-growth platform company with proven unit
economics, de-risked expansion potential, and strategic value to
multiple buyer categories.

**The combination of:**

• Waste-to-fertilizer core business\
• Carbon credit pipeline (151,200+ tCO₂e/year per site)\
• Strategic buyer synergies\
• 20-30 site rollout potential\
• First-mover advantage in Indonesian circular agriculture

**\...supports an exit valuation of \$250M--\$300M+ to strategic
acquirers who can execute the platform rollout.**

The key is positioning CFI not as a single-site operator, but as a
scalable platform that delivers waste valorization, soil health
improvement, and carbon credits across Indonesia\'s largest agricultural
sectors.

