**September 2026:** Horizon Europe Cluster 6 single-stage deadlines
(17--18 Sep).

**15.3 Regenerative Fund for Nature**

**Programme Overview**

The Regenerative Fund for Nature supports regenerative agriculture
pilots linked to major food and fibre brands. The fund prioritizes
projects that demonstrate measurable soil health improvements and
biodiversity benefits alongside commercial viability.

**Key Details**

  ----------------- ------------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**     **Details**

  Grant Size        US \$0.5--2 million (no mandatory match)

  Deadline          30 August 2025 (concept brief)

  Eligibility       NGO or SME with brand letter of support; Indonesia
                    eligible

  Focus Areas       Regenerative agriculture, soil health, biodiversity,
                    brand partnerships

  **Application**   **4-page concept brief, brand MoU, baseline metrics,
                    budget**
  ----------------- ------------------------------------------------------

**CFI Strategic Fit**

CFI\'s fertilizer improves soil organic matter content by 10--15% and
supports beneficial soil microbiome development. The chitin content
provides natural plant disease resistance, reducing chemical fungicide
requirements. These outcomes align directly with the fund\'s
regenerative agriculture priorities.

**Application Strategy**

CFI should approach palm oil majors (Wilmar, Golden Agri, Musim Mas) or
food brands with palm oil sourcing commitments (Nestlé, Unilever,
PepsiCo) for partnership letters. Existing field trial data from
Sucafina coffee trials and palm oil demonstrations provides ready-made
baseline metrics for the concept brief.

**15.4 USAID Indonesia Climate Adaptation & Circular Economy**

**Programme Overview**

USAID\'s Annual Program Statement (APS) for Indonesia supports circular
economy waste valorization, methane mitigation, and adaptive agriculture
projects. Round 2 EOIs are due October 2025 with full applications
invited on a rolling basis.

**Key Details**

  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**          **Details**

  Grant Size             US \$1--5 million

  Cost Share             1:1 preferred (50% co-financing)

  Deadline               15 October 2025 (Round 2 EOI)

  Eligibility            Indonesian or foreign NGO/for-profit able to
                         sign cooperative agreement

  Focus Areas            Circular economy waste valorization, methane
                         mitigation, adaptive agriculture

  **Application**        **5-page EOI, SAM/UEI registration, gender &
                         environmental screening**
  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------

**Application Requirements**

**SAM/UEI Registration:** CFI must register with the System for Award
Management (SAM.gov) and obtain a Unique Entity Identifier before
submission.

**Environmental Screening:** Preliminary environmental impact assessment
required, which CFI can derive from Verra ACM0022 documentation.

**Gender Integration:** Must demonstrate how project addresses gender
considerations in waste management and agricultural value chains.

**CFI Strategic Fit**

CFI\'s project directly addresses all three focus areas: converting
EFB/PKF waste to fertilizer (circular economy), avoiding methane
emissions (climate mitigation), and producing disease-suppressive
fertilizer for palm and coffee (adaptive agriculture). The 151,200 tCO₂e
annual methane avoidance provides compelling climate impact metrics.

**15.5 EU LIFE Programme 2025--2026**

**Programme Overview**

LIFE is the EU\'s primary funding instrument for environment and climate
action, with €5.4 billion allocated for 2021--2027. The Circular Economy
and Quality of Life sub-programme directly supports waste valorization,
resource recovery, and bio-based innovations.

**Circular Economy & Quality of Life Sub-Programme**

  ------------------ ----------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**      **Details**

  Total Budget       €697.5 million (sub-programme total)

  2025 Annual Budget €73 million (circular economy focus)

  Grant Size         €1--5 million typical; €10--30 million for Strategic
                     Integrated Projects

  Grant Rate         60% (Standard), 75% (Nature/Biodiversity), 95% (some
                     specific areas)

  Project Duration   3--5 years typical

  2025 Concept       Mid-January 2026 (portal opens October 2025)
  Deadline           

  **Eligibility**    **EU/EEA lead entity required; non-EU pilots allowed
                     if ≥50% spend in EU**
  ------------------ ----------------------------------------------------

**Priority Areas for CFI**

The LIFE programme explicitly prioritizes waste prevention and recovery
from agricultural residues, bio-based solutions replacing fossil-based
materials, and demonstration of circular business models. CFI\'s
technology addresses the Circular Economy Action Plan\'s objectives for
sustainable waste management and nutrient cycling.

**Application Strategy**

CFI requires an EU-based lead partner (research institution, NGO, or
company) to apply. Potential partners include Wageningen University
(Netherlands), CREA (Italy), or CIRAD (France) for agricultural
biotechnology expertise. The application should emphasize EU market
replication potential through olive and grape processing waste---15.2
million tonnes annually generating 36.7 million tCO₂e in methane
emissions.

**Key Application Requirements**

**Concept Note (Stage 1):** 10-page proposal outlining project scope,
methodology, expected impacts, and consortium composition. Due
mid-January 2026.

**Partner LOIs:** Letters of intent from all consortium members
confirming roles and commitments.

**Co-Financing Letters:** Evidence of 40% co-financing commitment (for
60% grant rate projects).

**EU Value Added:** Clear demonstration of benefits to EU environmental
policy objectives and replicability across member states.

**15.6 Green Climate Fund (GCF)**

**Programme Overview**

The Green Climate Fund is the world\'s largest multilateral climate
fund, supporting developing countries\' mitigation and adaptation
efforts. GCF-2 (2024--2027) has confirmed pledges of approximately US
\$9.6 billion. CFI\'s methane avoidance project qualifies under GCF\'s
mitigation window.

**Key Details**

  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**          **Details**

  Grant Size             Up to US \$10 million (grants); larger amounts
                         via loans

  Co-Financing           ≥1:1 expected (can include in-kind and parallel
                         financing)

  Deadline               Rolling submissions through Accredited Entities

  Access Modality        Via Accredited Entity (FAO, UNDP, ADB, or
                         national entities)

  Focus Areas            Methane avoidance, sustainable agriculture,
                         waste-to-value

  **Application**        **3-page Concept Note, NDA no-objection letter,
                         AE submission**
  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------

**Access Pathway**

CFI cannot apply directly to GCF; submissions must be made through an
Accredited Entity (AE). For Indonesia, suitable AEs include the Asian
Development Bank (regional AE), UNDP Indonesia, FAO, or PT Sarana Multi
Infrastruktur (national AE). The ADB pathway aligns well with CFI\'s
Technical Assistance strategy.

**Application Requirements**

**Concept Note:** 3-page summary including project rationale, expected
climate impacts (tCO₂e avoided), co-financing plan, and alignment with
Indonesia\'s NDC.

**NDA No-Objection:** Letter from Indonesia\'s National Designated
Authority (Ministry of Finance) confirming project alignment with
national priorities.

**Climate Impact Quantification:** CFI\'s Verra ACM0022 methodology
provides ready-made GHG quantification (151,200 tCO₂e/year).

**15.7 BPDPKS Palm Oil R&D / Downstream Grant**

**Programme Overview**

The Indonesia Palm Oil Fund Management Agency (BPDPKS) provides grants
for Indonesian R&D and downstream processing projects that add value to
palm residues. This is a strategic funding source given CFI\'s focus on
EFB and PKF valorization.

**Key Details**

  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**          **Details**

  Grant Size             IDR 10--50 billion (≈US \$0.65--3.3 million)

  Cash Counterpart       10% minimum

  Deadline               Rolling submissions

  Eligibility            Indonesian legal entity or joint venture with
                         Indonesian partner

  Focus Areas            Palm residue valorization, downstream
                         processing, R&D

  **Requirements**       **Detailed proposal, Indonesian entity
                         documentation, Tax ID (NPWP)**
  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------

**Strategic Fit**

CFI\'s technology converts EFB and PKF---the two largest palm oil mill
waste streams---into premium organic fertilizer that can be sold back to
palm plantations. This circular economy model directly addresses BPDPKS
priorities for downstream value addition and sustainable palm oil
production.

**Application Strategy**

CFI should establish or partner with an Indonesian legal entity (PT) to
access BPDPKS funding. The application should emphasize import
substitution value (replacing imported synthetic fertilizers), job
creation in rural palm oil regions, and alignment with Indonesia\'s B35
biodiesel and downstream industrialization policies.

**15.8 EIC Advanced Innovation Challenges**

**Programme Overview**

The European Innovation Council (EIC) Advanced Innovation Challenges
support breakthrough technologies from proof-of-concept (TRL 3--4) to
pre-commercial demonstration (TRL 5--7). The two-stage process provides
€300,000 for initial validation followed by up to €2.5 million for pilot
demonstration.

**Stage 1 Details**

  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**          **Details**

  Grant Amount           €300,000 lump sum

  Duration               9--10 months

  Starting TRL           TRL 3--4 (proof-of-concept validated in lab)

  Target TRL             TRL 5 (component validated in relevant
                         environment)

  Call Opening           3 December 2025

  Deadline               26 February 2026, 17:00 Brussels time

  **Application**        **11-page document (standard Horizon Europe
                         structure)**
  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------

**Stage 2 Details**

  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------
  **Parameter**          **Details**

  Grant Amount           Up to €2.5 million

  Target TRL             TRL 6--7 (technology demonstrated in relevant
                         environment)

  **Access**             **By invitation following successful Stage 1
                         completion**
  ---------------------- ------------------------------------------------

**CFI Application Strategy**

CFI should apply under the Marula Proteen methodology license for coffee
waste TRL 4--5 validation. The application can leverage existing field
trial data from Sucafina coffee trials, maize field trials, and
laboratory nutrient analyses to demonstrate proof-of-concept validation.

**Eligible Use of Proceeds**

Stage 1 funding can support prototype adaptation for new waste
feedstocks, testing and validation activities (lab and small-scale
pilots), material characterization and nutrient profiling, field or
greenhouse trials, business model development, and regulatory mapping
for EU market entry.

**Critical Success Factors**

  -------------- -------------------------- -----------------------------
  **Timeline**   **Milestone**              **Deliverable**

  Months 0--3    TRL 3/4 validation         Proof-of-concept validated,
                                            component design

  Month 3--4     TRL 4 achievement          All components validated in
                 (critical)                 lab environment

  Months 4--9    TRL 4→5 progression        Testing in relevant
                                            environment, data collection

  **Month        **Stage 1 completion**     **Pilot design finalized,
  9--10**                                   Stage 2 proposal ready**
  -------------- -------------------------- -----------------------------

**EU Relevance & Impact**

The EU imported 2 million tonnes of crude palm oil in 2024, requiring
approximately 10 million tonnes of FFB and generating 11 million tonnes
of EFB waste. Downstream methane emissions from this waste total
approximately 6.4 million tCO₂e annually. CFI\'s technology addresses
this specific EU supply chain impact. Additionally, EU-based replication
potential exists through olive processing waste (9.6 million
tonnes/year) and wine/grape processing waste (5.6 million tonnes/year),
with combined methane emissions of 36.7 million tCO₂e annually.

